% Run the three lines above.
% Copy-paste the line formatted in the command window to a vector (or to a cell array). 
% For example:
TextBlock = [1497 1513 32 1500 1504 1493 32 1506 1489 1512 1497 1514 32 33];
% If you want to check it in the command window you can simply use:
char([1497 1513 32 1500 1504 1493 32 1506 1489 1512 1497 1514 32 33])
% Now you can use the vector as the text input in the psychtoolbox text functions.
% If you need one line you can use "CenterText". For example:
CenterText(screen, TextBlock, [0 255 0],0,-30);
% If you need more than one line it is best to use "DrawFormattedText". For example:
DrawFormattedText(screen, TextBlock, 'center', 'center', [250 250 250]);
% To modify the space between the lines, use it this way:
DrawFormattedText(screen, TextBlock, 'center', 'center', [255 255 255], 0, 0, 0, 1.2) %The last parameter is the space between the lines.
% Then of course "Flip" etc...
% IMPORTANT NOTE: you have to use inside your code the formatted vector!
% Every time you close and open a matlab file, the hebrew letters will
% appear as question marks. Therefore you must use the pre-made numeric vectors inside your code. 

% Enjoy!
